  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">William Lloyd Garrison regrets not being able to attend the anti-slavery meeting in North Brookfield. Garrison is mentally and physically unfit to participate in public meetings due to his &quot;water &apos;crisis,&apos; in the development of humor and boils.&quot; Three of his children are sick with colds, coughs, and some fever. Garrison believes there is much prejudice &quot;against us&quot; in North Brookfield. He advises explaining their position rather than dealing severely with those &quot;who are not yet with us.&quot; The Free Soil movement should be hailed as proof of progress, though a higher position should be manifested. He suggests spending the heaviest ammunition on Zachary Taylor&apos;s party.</subfield>
  </datafield>
